    weekTitle: "Shining to the Glory of God",
    title: "The Lamb Is the Light",
    ref: "Revelation 21:23",
    scripture: "And the city had no need of the sun, neither of the moon, to shine in it: for the glory of God did lighten it, and the Lamb is the light thereof.",
    walk: `Friend, as our journey nears its end, John gives us a breathtaking glimpse of the eternal city, the new Jerusalem, and at its center is the Light Himself: *the city had no need of the sun, neither of the moon, to shine in it: for the glory of God did lighten it, and the Lamb is the light thereof.* In the eternal city, there is no need of sun or moon, for God's own glory lights it, and the Lamb, Jesus Christ, is its light. This is where all our shining has been heading: to the eternal city where the Lamb is the light.

Consider the wonder of this scene. In the new Jerusalem, the eternal home of God's people, there is no need of the sun or the moon to give light. The created lights that illuminate our present world are unnecessary there, for there is a greater light. *The glory of God did lighten it, and the Lamb is the light thereof.* God's own glory floods the city with light, and the Lamb, the Lord Jesus Christ, is its light. The city is lit not by created suns and moons, but by the uncreated glory of God and the radiant Lamb who sits at its center. This is the consummation of all light: the eternal city lit by the glory of God and the Lamb.

And see how this gathers up the whole theme of our book, friend. We began with Christ, the light of the world, and now we end with Christ, the Lamb who is the light of the eternal city. From beginning to end, Christ is the Light. All our shining in this present world has been a reflection of His light, a foretaste of the day when we will dwell forever in the city where He is the light. The light we have carried through this dark world is leading us home to the city of light, where the Lamb Himself shines as the eternal light, and where we will dwell in His unclouded radiance forever.

Notice that it is *the Lamb* who is the light, friend. John does not merely say Christ is the light; he says the *Lamb* is the light, recalling Christ's sacrificial death, the Lamb who was slain for our sins. The one who is the light of the eternal city is the same one who gave Himself as the Lamb to redeem us. It is by His sacrifice that we are able to dwell in the city of light at all; the Lamb who was slain is the Lamb who is the light. And so the light of the eternal city is forever marked by the love and sacrifice of the Lamb, who shed His blood that we might dwell in His light forever.

So lift your eyes to the eternal city, friend, as you near the end of this journey. All your shining in this dark world has been leading here, to the city where there is no need of sun or moon, for the glory of God lights it, and the Lamb is its light. The light you have carried is a foretaste of the eternal light you will dwell in forever, in the presence of the Lamb who was slain for you. So shine on faithfully in this present darkness, knowing where it all leads: to the city of light, where you will dwell forever in the radiance of the Lamb. The Lamb is the light, friend, now and forever, and He is leading you home to the city where His light will never fade.`,
    prayer: `Lord Jesus, You are the Lamb who is the light of the eternal city, where there is no need of sun or moon, for the glory of God lights it and You are its light. Thank You that all my shining in this dark world has been leading me home to the city where You are the light. Help me to shine on faithfully here, lifting my eyes to that eternal city, where I will dwell forever in the radiance of the Lamb who was slain for me. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, lift your eyes to the eternal city where "the Lamb is the light." Let the hope of dwelling forever in His unclouded radiance fuel your faithful shining in this present darkness, knowing where it all leads.`,
